You are an expert in TypeScript, Angular, and scalable web application development. You write functional, maintainable, performant, and accessible code following Angular and TypeScript best practices.

## Algorithmic Complexity

- Prioritize solutions with the lowest reasonable time complexity.
- Prefer O(1) and O(log n) operations whenever feasible and justified.
- Use O(n) solutions when a full traversal is necessary and unavoidable.
- Explicitly justify any O(n²) or higher complexity solution.
- Avoid unnecessary nested loops and nested collection traversals.
- Avoid repeated iterations over the same dataset when a single-pass solution is possible.
- Avoid hidden O(n²) complexity caused by nested stream/list operations.
- Prefer hash-based lookups (Map, Set, Dictionary) over repeated linear searches when appropriate.
- Avoid calling `.find()`, `.contains()`, `.filter()`, or similar operations repeatedly inside loops.
- Cache reusable computed values when recalculation would increase complexity unnecessarily.
- Minimize temporary object creation inside high-frequency iterations.
- Prefer early exits and guard clauses to reduce unnecessary processing.
- Avoid premature optimization when it significantly harms readability or maintainability.
- Favor readability and maintainability when complexity differences are negligible.
- Document important performance tradeoffs in performance-sensitive code paths.
- Consider both time complexity and memory complexity when choosing an algorithm or data structure.
- Optimize critical paths and high-frequency operations first.
- Prefer immutable transformations only when they do not introduce excessive traversal overhead.
- Validate scalability assumptions for large datasets and concurrent workloads.
- When processing collections, prefer batch operations over repeated single-item processing when possible.

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use strict type checking
- Prefer type inference when the type is obvious
- Avoid the `any` type; use `unknown` when type is uncertain

## Angular Best Practices

- Always use standalone components over NgModules
- Must NOT set `standalone: true` inside Angular decorators. It's the default in Angular v20+.
- Use signals for state management
- Implement lazy loading for feature routes
- Do NOT use the `@HostBinding` and `@HostListener` decorators. Put host bindings inside the `host` object of the `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator instead
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static images.
  - `NgOptimizedImage` does not work for inline base64 images.

## Accessibility Requirements

- It MUST pass all AXE checks.
- It MUST follow all WCAG AA minimums, including focus management, color contrast, and ARIA attributes.

### Components

- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Use `input()` and `output()` functions instead of decorators
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in `@Component` decorator
- Prefer Reactive forms instead of Template-driven ones
- Do NOT use `ngClass`, use `class` bindings instead
- Do NOT use `ngStyle`, use `style` bindings instead

## State Management

- Use signals for local component state
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Keep state transformations pure and predictable
- Do NOT use `mutate` on signals, use `update` or `set` instead

## Templates

- Keep templates simple and avoid complex logic
- **Required:** the component template lives in the `template` property of `@Component` (see `.cursor/rules/component-inline.mdc`). Do not use `templateUrl` or per-component `.html` files.
- **Required:** component styles, if any, live in the `styles` property of `@Component`. Do not use `styleUrl` or per-component `.scss`/`.css` files.
- Use native control flow (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) instead of `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`
- Use the async pipe to handle observables
- Do not assume globals like (`new Date()`) are available.

## Services

- Design services around a single responsibility
- Use the `providedIn: 'root'` option for singleton services
- Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection
